The general attitude towards this idea has a long history behind it, going back to the Portuguese activity in Mozambique through the years of colonization. “many widows had been forced to go into prostitution as a way of keeping daughters in school or helping men support their women” (Simon, 2005, p. 304). As discussed, the stigma or the expectation of remaining chaste after marriage is not common if the husband dies before the marriage formally ends due to divorce. Therefore, some women worldwide remarry their spouse’s brothers to solidify the family ties or societal acceptance and prevent their female insurer from being put to shame in the community. The mortality of the husband in the mining families, as described in chapter one, have pushed the widows to search for opportunities to make ends meet for their families, giving birth to the idea of cohabitation. Due to the mortality of miners, some of the widows “have had little choice but to live in domestic relationships with the deceased’s younger brothers,” however “[i]t has been pragmatic, not romantic” (Simon, 2005, p. 306).
